Hi @lukeapage,

one last question about the FileManager API. My Less plugin to resolve Bower imports is nearly complete. Besides the one issue with auto-appended Less extensions (https://github.com/less/less.js/issues/2235) I have one more Bower-specific edge case:

Many Less developers use import files like [these](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/master/less/bootstrap.less). Bower however allows you to place these references into the `bower.json`. It could look like this:

```
{
  "main": [
    "variables.less",
    "mixins.less"
  ]
}
```

My `resolve` function returns an array of filenames in this case and I would like to know how I should handle `loadFile` than? I see two possibilities:

**1) Merge files**

I could basically call the `loadFile` function multiple times and return the merged result. It could look something like that:

```
BowerFileManager.prototype.loadFile = function(filename, currentDirectory, options, environment) {
        var that = this;
        return this.resolve(filename, currentDirectory).then(function(filenames) {
            // this.resolve is a promise which returns an array of filenames
            // most of the time it just contains one filename, but sometimes a bower.json
            // references multiple less files

            // we can create multiple loadFile-promises and wait for all of them with Q.all
            return Q.all(filenames.map(function(filename) {
                return FileManager.prototype.loadFile.call(that, filename, '', options, environment);
            })).then(function(files) {
                // reduce returned loaded files to one file
                return files.reduce(function(previousValue, currentValue, index, array) {
                    // concatenating contents is no problem...
                    previousValue.contents += '\n' + currentValue.contents;
                    // TODO: How to handle previousValue.filename?
                    return previousValue;
                });
            });
        });
    };
```

I can concatenate the `contents` easily, but how should I handle `filename`? When is `filename` used - I guess in the source maps?

**2) Create virtual file**

When I detect a `bower.json` I could just dynamically create a virtual less file and set its filepath to the `bower.json`.

```
{
  "main": [
    "variables.less",
    "mixins.less"
  ]
}
```

becomes

```
{
  contents: '@import "variables.less"\n@import "mixins.less";',
  filename: 'some-module/bower.json'
}
```

I think this would work quite well, but maybe this is an unnecessary bloated step...? 

What do you think?
